            ">Central Asia‚Äôs water crisis</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: Central Asia is facing water scarcity due to climate change and inadequate management. </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The what:</strong> Central Asia is facing a severe <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-water-security-crisis" target="_blank">water security crisis</a> due to climate change and poor management. Glaciers are melting faster than the global average, destabilizing river flows that support agriculture, energy, and drinking water. Aging Soviet-era systems dried up the rivers and increased their salinity. The UN warns that up to 5Mn Central Asians will be exposed to climate-induced migration by 2050. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The context:</strong> During the Soviet era, large-scale irrigation projects aimed at increasing cotton production had a detrimental impact on the natural water cycle. The key rivers were overexploited, leading to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-the-near-disappearance" target="_blank">the near disappearance</a> of the Aral Sea. The water was managed collectively, but unsustainably.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         After the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the five Central Asian republics faced competing national interests over shared rivers. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The challenge:</strong> The Tajikistan-Kyrgyzstan-Uzbekistan border agreement and the Hujand Declaration showcase that the region is moving towards cooperation in water management. However, challenges, including a lack of strategic alignment, weak institutional power, and issues with data sharing and transparency, pose a threat to long-term cooperation. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Read our full report on the crisis <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-here" target="_blank">here</a>.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
