        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="
              font-size: 16px;
              line-height: 1.5;
              padding-top: 0px;
              padding-bottom: 6px;
            ">
            <strong>üá∏üá© Sudan - Rival government formed.</strong> The RSF paramilitary group has announced a rival government to challenge the military powers in Khartoum directly. This coalition, led by ‚ÄúHemedti‚Äù Dagalo, will chair a 15-member presidential council, which includes regional governors. It risks creating parallel states while many face violence, famine, and displacement (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-worldwide-10-conflict-continues" target="_blank">conflict continues</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
          <strong>üá∫üá¶ Ukraine - Aid suspended.</strong> The EU has suspended $1.7B in aid to Ukraine as the nation failed to meet anti-corruption benchmarks. These conditions include the appointment of a judge to the Anti-Corruption Court, as the EU expressed concerns over the transparency of the agency. This can be a huge setback for Ukraine, as it depends on European and American support for its defense against Russia (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-worldwide-11-backsliding-reform" target="_blank">backsliding reform</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
         <strong>üá™üá∫ EU - Too soft on Azerbaijan.</strong> The EU is being accused of being silent about the repression in Azerbaijan under President Aliyev over oil favors from Baku. One of the most recent incidents includes the EU's silence behind the jailing of peace activist Bahruz Samadov. Critics say the EU‚Äôs inaction weakens its human rights message and boosts authoritarianism in a region looking for options beyond Russian influence (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-worldwide-12-double-standards" target="_blank">double standards</a>). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
         <strong>üáÆüá≥ India - Easing tensions with the Maldives.</strong> Indian PM Narendra Modi's trip to the Maldives was a diplomatic reset with pro-China President Mohamed Muizzu. Modi promised $565M in aid and initiated trade talks. The visit came as ties improved after earlier tensions over the Indian military presence, tourism competition, and Muizzu's shift toward Beijing (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-worldwide-13-new-chapters" target="_blank">new chapters</a>).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; padding-bottom: 6px">
         <strong>üá≤üáæ Malaysia - Mediates conflict.</strong> Thailand and Cambodia will begin talks in Malaysia to end four days of deadly border clashes that have killed at least 33 people. President Trump urged both sides to agree to a ceasefire, using a future trade agreement as an incentive towards peace. The conflict stems from a historic border dispute, with both nations blaming each other for initiating hostilities (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-worldwide-14-malay-peace-brokers" target="_blank">Malay peace brokers</a>).
          </p>
        </mj-text>
