              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Why is Germany slower to react to Gaza? </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/reason-of-state-in-international-relations.jpg" alt="The Reason of state is a legal theory and concept in international relations that has evolved over centuries of Western political thought, as the role, rights, and powers of the state have developed" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>The "Reason of state" is a concept in international relations that has evolved over centuries of Western political thought, as the role, rights, and powers of the state have developed. Credits: Getty Images</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> Germany has been criticized repeatedly for being one of the bigger European powers that has been the slowest to condemn Israel for its actions in Gaza. It was notably absent from the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-foundations-h1-15-list-of-28-countries" target="_blank">list of 28 countries</a> that made a joint statement calling for Israel to end the war in Gaza and resume humanitarian aid. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>The reason:</strong> Germany adheres to the Staatsraison (reason of state) principle, which adds a moral responsibility that Germany should prioritize providing security to Israel as part of its core national interest. This is rooted in the Nazi-era history of ill-treatment of Jews and the Holocaust. They also have domestic policies at stake, as Germany has one of the largest Jewish and Muslim populations in Europe, putting it in a delicate position. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
        <strong>The future:</strong> Public opinion on Israel‚Äôs actions is <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-becoming-less-favorable" target="_blank">becoming less favorable</a>, with the latest showing that just 36% of Germans support it. However, Germany is led by the conservative CDU party, whose foreign policy framework strongly favors Israel. This makes it more challenging to take a stronger role in the Israel-Gaza war. However, public pressure is slowly taking a toll on the German government, as last weekend, Germany joined France and the UK <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-in-pressing-israel" target="_blank">in pressing Israel</a> for a ceasefire. 
          </p>
           <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
        Know more about Germany‚Äôs unique relationship with Israel <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-here" target="_blank">here</a>. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
